<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S. CONDUCTS FIRST NUCLEAR TEST OF 1989 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MERCURY, Nev. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
U.S. scientists conducted their first underground nuclear weapons test of 1989 
on Friday. The blast rocked the desert with a force of a magnitude 5.1 
earthquake, the National Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo., 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
Slight motion was detected in some high-rise buildings in Las Vegas, 80 miles 
from ground zero. 
</P>
<P>
"The control point building is rocking," said Energy Department spokesman Jim 
Boyer, who was at the control center 7.5 miles from ground zero. Detonation was 
at 12:06 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
The test, code-named Texarkana, had been scheduled for Thursday morning but was 
delayed by snow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
